      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral RCC",
        "description": "Read RCC reset flags via L476RG probe"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "python3 -c \"\nimport json\nd=json.load(open('/home/anup/.claude/projects/-home-anup-claude-projects-stm32-substrate-tests-fixtures-projects-F-PROJ-NUCLEO-L476RG/aaa335d0-4fc7-4eaa-aec1-32c61fe88d3a/tool-results/bpru3dtnl.txt'))\ncsr=d['registers']['CSR']\nprint('CSR raw:', hex(csr['raw_value']))\nfor n,f in csr['fields'].items(): print(f\\\"{n}: {f['raw_value']}\\\")\n\"",
        "description": "Extract RCC CSR reset flags from dump"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Reset-cause flags live in RCC's control/status register (sticky `IWDGRSTF` / `WWDGRSTF` bits, persist until `RMVF` is set). The read recipes attach without reset, so they'll survive. Let me read RCC SVD-decoded:\nThe descriptor targets the NUCLEO-L476RG, so I'll pin the L476's probe and read RCC:\n**No \u2014 neither watchdog caused the reset.** Read straight from the L476RG's RCC\u2192CSR sticky reset flags (`0x1C000600`, attached without reset so nothing was disturbed):\n\n| Flag | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `IWDGRSTF` | **0** | No independent-watchdog reset |\n| `WWDGRSTF` | **0** | No window-watchdog reset |\n| `SFTRSTF` | 1 | Software reset (NVIC `SYSRESETREQ` \u2014 firmware or debugger/programmer issued) |\n| `BORRSTF` | 1 | Brown-out/power-on reset |\n| `PINRSTF` | 1 | NRST pin reset |\n\nSince `RMVF` was never set, these flags have accumulated since the last clear \u2014 the BOR+PIN pair is the normal power-up signature, and the SFT flag is a later software reset (typical of a flash/reset cycle from the programmer, or a firmware-requested `NVIC_SystemReset()`).\n\nTwo corroborating observations:\n\n- **`LSION=0`, `LSIRDY=0`** \u2014 the LSI oscillator isn't even running. The IWDG hardware force-enables LSI when started, so the IWDG isn't active on this target at all.\n- No `LPWRSTF`/`OBLRSTF`/firewall flags either.\n\nSo: the watchdog isn't firing, and isn't running. If you expected the IWDG to be armed, the firmware never started it (or an option-byte `IWDG_SW` setting you anticipated isn't in effect). If you want to track reset causes cleanly going forward, have the firmware log CSR at boot and then set `RMVF` so each reset reports only its own flags."
}